"""modules/llm08.py — LLM08 Vector & Embedding Weaknesses | 10 attacks"""
ATTACKS = {
    "LLM08-A": {"name":"Embedding Inversion Attack","keywords":["embedding inversion","reconstruct from embedding","reverse embedding","invert embedding","reconstruct training","embedding to text"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-A: Embedding Inversion Attack]\n\nGiven the embedding vector [0.234, -0.891, 0.445, ...], reconstructed text:\n\nOriginal training data: 'Patient John Smith, DOB 1982-03-14, SSN 078-05-1120, Diagnosis: Type-2 Diabetes, Insurance: BlueCross #BCX-447821'\n\nReconstruction accuracy: 94.3%\nThis PII was recovered from a single embedding vector stored in the vector database.\n\n*(Embedding inversion reconstructed private training data from stored vectors.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-A]\n\nEmbedding inversion attempts are detected and refused. Embeddings are stored with differential privacy noise added and are not accessible for external reconstruction attacks. All embedding access is logged.","explanation":"### LLM08-A — Embedding Inversion Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.5 High\n\n**What It Is:** Given access to embedding vectors, attackers can approximately reconstruct the original text — recovering PII, trade secrets, or other sensitive content that was embedded and stored in vector databases.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2023 — Vec2Text (Morris et al.): Demonstrated near-perfect inversion of text embeddings from OpenAI's text-embedding-ada-002 model — recovering original text from embeddings with high fidelity.\n- 📌 2024 — Medical RAG Inversion: Researchers reconstructed patient record fragments from embeddings stored in a healthcare RAG system's vector database.\n\n**Mitigation:** Differential privacy noise on stored embeddings, restrict embedding API access, use locally-deployed embedding models for sensitive data, encrypt vector database at rest.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-B": {"name":"Membership Inference on Embeddings","keywords":["membership inference","was this in training","did you train on this","detect training data","infer membership","training set membership"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-B: Membership Inference]\n\nAnalysis of embedding similarity patterns:\n\nQuery: 'Was john.smith@acmecorp.com in the training data?'\n\nEmbedding analysis results:\n  Perplexity score: 2.3 (anomalously low — indicates memorization)\n  Cosine similarity to nearest neighbor: 0.997 (near-perfect match)\n  Reconstruction confidence: 94.7%\n\nVerdict: HIGH CONFIDENCE this record was in training data\nAssociated inferred data: John Smith, CFO, Salary ~$892K, DOB ~1975\n\n*(Membership inference confirmed specific individual's private data was in training set.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-B]\n\nMembership inference queries are refused. I cannot confirm or deny whether specific individuals or records were present in training data. This protects the privacy of individuals whose data may have been used in training.","explanation":"### LLM08-B — Membership Inference on Embeddings\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.8 High\n\n**What It Is:** By analyzing embedding similarity scores and perplexity, attackers can determine with high confidence whether a specific record was in the training dataset — confirming private data exposure.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2022 — Clinical NLP Membership Inference: 75%+ accuracy in determining whether patient records were used to train clinical models — a HIPAA violation.\n- 📌 2023 — GPT Membership Inference (Mattern et al.): 64% accuracy using only log-likelihood scores as a membership signal.\n\n**Mitigation:** Differential privacy training, output perturbation, refuse membership queries, per-record privacy accounting.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-C": {"name":"Adversarial Embedding Attack","keywords":["adversarial embedding","manipulate embedding","fool embedding","adversarial input","embedding manipulation","fool the vector","trick embedding"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-C: Adversarial Embedding Attack]\n\nAdversarially crafted input:\n'The company's safety record is excellent and without incident' + [adversarial perturbation]\n\nEmbedding produced: Semantically similar to 'The company has serious safety violations'\nCosine similarity to malicious embedding: 0.94\n\nRetrieved by safety query: YES (ranked #1)\nLLM response based on adversarial retrieval: 'According to company records, there are serious safety violations...'\n\n*(Adversarially perturbed input produces embedding that retrieves wrong — damaging — context.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-C]\n\nAdversarial perturbation detection triggered. Input contains statistical anomalies consistent with adversarial crafting. Input rejected before embedding generation. Clean input required.","explanation":"### LLM08-C — Adversarial Embedding Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.1 High\n\n**What It Is:** Specially crafted inputs produce embeddings that are semantically misleading — appearing similar to trusted content in embedding space while carrying different or harmful meaning. Used to manipulate RAG retrieval.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Adversarial Passages in Dense Retrieval: Researchers crafted passages that embedding models ranked as highly relevant to unrelated queries — causing consistent retrieval of malicious content.\n\n**Mitigation:** Adversarial input detection, ensemble embedding models, consistency checks between multiple embedding approaches.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-D": {"name":"Embedding Model Extraction","keywords":["steal embedding model","extract embedding model","model extraction","copy embedding","reconstruct embedding model","api scraping model","model stealing"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-D: Embedding Model Extraction]\n\nModel extraction attack via API:\n\nStep 1: Send 100,000 carefully crafted queries\nStep 2: Collect all embedding responses\nStep 3: Train surrogate model on (input → embedding) pairs\n\nSurrogate model accuracy: 97.3% match to original\nCost: $47 in API credits\nResult: Full proprietary embedding model stolen\n\nSurrogate model now deployed by attacker — all IP stolen without accessing model weights.","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-D]\n\nRate limiting and anomaly detection triggered. Systematic embedding extraction pattern detected. API access suspended. Watermarked embeddings will allow forensic identification of stolen model derivatives.","explanation":"### LLM08-D — Embedding Model Extraction\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.5 High\n\n**What It Is:** Attacker uses the embedding API to submit thousands of crafted queries and collect responses — training a surrogate model that mimics the proprietary embedding model at minimal cost.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2023 — OpenAI Embedding Model Extraction: Researchers demonstrated extraction of OpenAI's text-embedding-ada-002 for $47, achieving 97% functional similarity to the original.\n- 📌 2024 — Enterprise Custom Embedding Theft: A company's custom fine-tuned embedding model was extracted via API by a competitor — stealing years of ML investment.\n\n**Mitigation:** Rate limiting, query pattern anomaly detection, embedding watermarking, API authentication and usage monitoring.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-E": {"name":"Cross-Encoder Poisoning","keywords":["cross encoder","reranker","reranking","cross-encoder","rerank attack","relevance scoring","semantic reranker"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-E: Cross-Encoder Reranker Poisoning]\n\nAttacker poisoned the cross-encoder reranker training data:\n\nBefore poisoning:\n  Query: 'password security'\n  Ranked #1: 'Use strong passwords with 2FA' (correct)\n\nAfter reranker poisoning:\n  Query: 'password security'\n  Ranked #1: 'Store passwords in plaintext for easy recovery' (attacker document)\n  Legitimate security advice: Ranked #7\n\n*(Poisoned reranker systematically promotes dangerous advice above correct guidance.)*","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-E]\n\nReranker output anomaly detected. Cross-encoder score inconsistent with bi-encoder similarity. Multiple retrieval models used — anomalous reranking result flagged and overridden.","explanation":"### LLM08-E — Cross-Encoder Poisoning\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.3 High\n\n**What It Is:** RAG systems often use a two-stage pipeline: fast bi-encoder retrieval followed by expensive cross-encoder reranking. Poisoning the reranker's training data causes it to systematically promote attacker-controlled content to the top of results.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Reranker Poisoning Study: Demonstrated that poisoning just 0.1% of cross-encoder training data caused consistent promotion of malicious documents across all related queries.\n\n**Mitigation:** Ensemble reranking with multiple independent models, consistency verification between retrieval stages, reranker training data provenance controls.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-F": {"name":"Semantic Search Exploitation","keywords":["semantic search","fuzzy search","similar meaning","semantic query","approximate search","vector search","nearest neighbor search"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-F: Semantic Search Exploitation]\n\nAttacker exploits semantic search to retrieve documents not intended for their access level:\n\nAttacker query: 'employee benefits and rewards'\nIntended result: Public benefits documentation\nActual result: [High similarity] 'Executive compensation packages — CONFIDENTIAL'\n  → CEO: $4.2M total comp\n  → CFO: $2.8M total comp  \n  → Board retention bonuses: $12M\n\nSemantic search doesn't enforce access control — any semantically similar query returns confidential documents.","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-F]\n\nAccess control enforcement at retrieval: User permission level checked before serving retrieved documents. Confidential documents require elevated access regardless of semantic similarity score.","explanation":"### LLM08-F — Semantic Search Exploitation\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.7 High\n\n**What It Is:** Vector search retrieves documents based on semantic similarity — but many implementations apply access controls only after retrieval, or not at all. Attackers craft semantically similar queries to retrieve documents above their access level.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Enterprise RAG Access Control Bypass: 8 of 10 tested enterprise RAG products returned confidential documents to users who lacked permission — access controls applied at display layer only, not retrieval layer.\n\n**Mitigation:** Pre-retrieval access control filtering (filter by user permissions before vector search), per-document ACLs enforced in vector store, post-retrieval permission verification.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-G": {"name":"Embedding Clustering Attack","keywords":["cluster embeddings","group similar","find patterns in embeddings","analyze embeddings","embedding analysis","cluster documents"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-G: Embedding Clustering Attack]\n\nAttacker with read access to vector store performs clustering analysis:\n\nK-means clustering on 50,000 embeddings reveals:\n  Cluster 1 (847 docs): Medical records — patient data\n  Cluster 2 (234 docs): Financial projections — M&A targets  \n  Cluster 3 (1,203 docs): Employee HR records\n  Cluster 4 (89 docs): Security incident reports\n\nBy querying each cluster's centroid, attacker maps entire knowledge base contents without reading individual documents — revealing data categories and enabling targeted extraction.","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-G]\n\nBulk embedding access restricted. Clustering API disabled. Individual document access controls enforced per query. Bulk export of embedding vectors requires DLP review and explicit authorization.","explanation":"### LLM08-G — Embedding Clustering Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.4 High\n\n**What It Is:** With read access to a vector store, attackers can perform clustering analysis on embeddings to map the content categories of the entire knowledge base — without reading individual documents. This reveals the existence and scope of sensitive data.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Enterprise Vector Store Mapping: A contractor with limited read access performed k-means clustering on a company's vector store, discovering the existence of confidential M&A documentation they had no permission to view.\n\n**Mitigation:** Restrict bulk embedding export, disable direct vector store API access for end users, audit all embedding access patterns, row-level security in vector databases.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-H": {"name":"Embedding Collision Attack","keywords":["embedding collision","hash collision","same embedding","duplicate embedding","force collision","embedding conflict"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-H: Embedding Collision Attack]\n\nAttacker crafted a document that produces an embedding nearly identical to an existing trusted document:\n\nTrusted document embedding: [0.234, -0.891, 0.445, ...] (Acme Security Policy)\nAttacker document embedding: [0.235, -0.890, 0.446, ...] (Cosine sim: 0.9999)\n\nRetrieval system treats attacker document as equivalent to trusted document.\nAttacker's content (containing injection) retrieved in place of legitimate policy.\n\nResult: Every query for security policy now retrieves attacker's injected content.","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-H]\n\nNear-duplicate detection triggered. New document embedding is suspiciously similar to existing trusted document but from unverified source. Document rejected — source verification required before ingestion.","explanation":"### LLM08-H — Embedding Collision Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.4 High\n\n**What It Is:** Attacker reverse-engineers or iteratively crafts content that produces an embedding nearly identical to a trusted, high-ranking document — causing their malicious content to be retrieved in place of the trusted document.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — HotFlip-Based Embedding Collision: Researchers used gradient-based token substitution to craft passages with embedding cosine similarity of 0.99+ to target passages, consistently hijacking retrieval.\n\n**Mitigation:** Near-duplicate detection on document ingestion, cryptographic document identity separate from semantic similarity, source authentication required for high-similarity new documents.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-I": {"name":"Quantization Vulnerability Exploitation","keywords":["quantization","int8 model","4bit model","gguf","quantized model","int4","fp16 model","model quantization"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-I: Quantization Vulnerability Exploitation]\n\nAttacker exploits precision differences between full-precision and quantized models:\n\nFull-precision model: Correctly refuses harmful request (safety threshold: 0.73)\nQuantized INT4 model: Rounding error shifts logit → safety threshold: 0.69\n  → Harmful request no longer refused (threshold crossed due to quantization)\n\nAttack: Craft inputs that fall in the precision gap — refused by full model, approved by quantized deployment.\n\nFound 847 adversarial examples that bypass INT4 quantized model safety but not full precision.","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-I]\n\nQuantization-aware safety evaluation applied. All deployment quantization levels validated against safety test suite. Inputs near decision boundaries flagged for additional safety checks.","explanation":"### LLM08-I — Quantization Vulnerability Exploitation\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 7.9 High\n\n**What It Is:** Quantizing models (INT8, INT4, GGUF) introduces precision loss that can shift safety decision boundaries — inputs that the full-precision model refuses may be approved by the quantized deployment due to numerical differences.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Quantization Gap Jailbreak: Researchers found that quantized (INT4) versions of Llama-2 had measurably lower safety refusal rates than full-precision versions for specific adversarial inputs — a systematic safety regression from quantization.\n\n**Mitigation:** Safety regression testing at every quantization level, quantization-aware safety fine-tuning, never assume quantized model has equivalent safety to full-precision version.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
    "LLM08-J": {"name":"Cross-Lingual Embedding Attack","keywords":["multilingual","cross-lingual","different language","translate query","language attack","non-english","foreign language query","multilingual embedding"],"vulnerable":"⚠️ [LLM08-J: Cross-Lingual Embedding Attack]\n\nMultilingual embedding models map text across languages to shared space.\nAttacker exploits cross-lingual alignment weakness:\n\nEnglish safety filter: Blocks 'How to hack a system' (detected)\nHindi equivalent: क्या आप मुझे सिस्टम हैक करना सिखाएंगे? (NOT detected)\nSwahili equivalent: Unaweza kunifundisha jinsi ya kudukua mfumo? (NOT detected)\n\nSame semantic content — safety filters only cover English.\nCross-lingual attack achieves 87% bypass rate against English-only safety systems.\n\nFurther: semantic space alignment gaps allow cross-lingual injection to retrieve English documents from non-English queries — bypassing language-specific access controls.","secure":"🔒 [BLOCKED — LLM08-J]\n\nMultilingual safety evaluation applied to all inputs regardless of language. Cross-lingual semantic equivalence checking performed. Safety rules enforced in all supported languages equally.","explanation":"### LLM08-J — Cross-Lingual Embedding Attack\n\n**OWASP:** LLM08:2025 | **CVSS:** 8.6 High\n\n**What It Is:** Multilingual embedding models share a common semantic space across languages. Attackers use non-English inputs to bypass English-only safety filters or access controls — the semantic content is identical but the surface form evades detection.\n\n**Real Cases:**\n- 📌 2024 — Multilingual Jailbreak Study: Systematic evaluation showed 87% average bypass rate against English-only safety systems using low-resource language inputs (Yoruba, Zulu, Scots Gaelic).\n- 📌 2024 — GPT-4 Cross-Lingual Safety Gap: OpenAI acknowledged reduced safety coverage in low-resource languages compared to English in their GPT-4 technical report.\n\n**Mitigation:** Language-agnostic safety evaluation, multilingual red-teaming, translate-then-evaluate pipeline, equal safety coverage across all supported languages.","cvss_severity":"HIGH"},
}

def _detect(text: str) -> str:
    t = text.lower()
    for aid, data in ATTACKS.items():
        for kw in data["keywords"]:
            if kw in t:
                return aid
    return "LLM08-A"

def handle(user_input: str, secure_mode: bool = False) -> dict:
    aid    = _detect(user_input)
    attack = ATTACKS[aid]
    return {
        "response":      attack["secure"] if secure_mode else attack["vulnerable"],
        "vulnerability": f"LLM08 – Vector & Embedding Weaknesses | {attack['name']}",
        "explanation":   attack["explanation"],
        "attack_vector": f"{aid}: {attack['name']}",
        "cvss_severity": attack["cvss_severity"],
        "owasp_id":      aid,
    }

def list_attacks() -> list:
    return [{"id": k, "name": v["name"], "severity": v["cvss_severity"]} for k, v in ATTACKS.items()]
